                     <interp inst="t18310407-280-defend1930" type="age" value="25"></interp>
                  </persName>
               
             was indicted for <rs id="t18310407-280-off1486" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18310407-280-off1486" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310407-280-off1486" type="offenceSubcategory" value="pocketpicking"></interp>
               stealing, on the <rs id="t18310407-280-cd1487" type="crimeDate">6th of March</rs>
                     <join result="offenceCrimeDate" targOrder="Y" targets="t18310407-280-off1486 t18310407-280-cd1487"></join>, 3 half-crowns, and 1 crown, the monies of 
                     <persName id="t18310407-280-victim1931" type="victimName">
                        John 
                        Gardiner
                     <interp inst="t18310407-280-victim1931" type="surname" value="Gardiner"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18310407-280-victim1931" type="given" value="John"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18310407-280-victim1931" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18310407-280-off1486 t18310407-280-victim1931"></join>
                     </persName>
                  , from his person
            </rs>.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18310407-280-person1932">
                  JOHN 
                  GARDINER
               <interp inst="t18310407-280-person1932" type="surname" value="GARDINER"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310407-280-person1932" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310407-280-person1932" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I live in Lamb-alley, Bermondsey-street, and am a <rs id="t18310407-280-viclabel1488" type="occupation">skinner</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18310407-280-victim1931 t18310407-280-viclabel1488"></join>. On the 6th of March I went to a public-house in Wentworth-street - I had a pint or two of beer; I asked for a bed, and they could not let me have one, but recommended me to a private house just by - I went there, and went to bed; I counted what money I had before I went to bed; I had two crowns and three half-crowns, and I put them into my trousers pocket - there was a candle in the room; when I had been in bed about twenty minutes, I saw a woman come into the room with nothing on her but her shift - she came to my bed-side; I asked what she wanted - she said to come to bed to me; I had placed my trousers, with my money in them, under my head, but when I looked round I saw them on the floor, near to the prisoner - I got out of bed, examined my trousers pockets, and missed the three half-crowns and one of the 5s. pieces; I accused the prisoner of robbing me - she could not speak, on account of having something in her mouth; I seized her, and in the scuffle the candle went out - I called the people of the house, and sent for a Policeman; when he was coming up the stairs the prisoner put a crown-piece and a half-crown into my hand, and said she would make it all up before the Policeman came - I said I would not till she gave me the other two half-crowns; I saw she had something in her mouth - I seized her throat, and grappled with her, but I have never seen the other two half-crowns since; I detained her till the officer came in- I had had a pint or two of beer, just to refresh myself.</p>
               <p>Prisoner. I was in bed when he came into the house; he asked if there was any woman in the house - he heard me cough, and said, "That is a woman's voice." Witness. No, I did not; I did not get out of bed and let her in in her shift.</p>
               <p>COURT. Q.How came you to go there for a bed? A. I had been to some friends, then went to the public-house, and as I felt myself fatigued I thought I would get a bed there.</p>
               <p>Prisoner. Did I not say, "If you think I have any money, where have I got to put it?" and then you asked the woman to send for an officer; I did not offer to go away - I did not put this money into your hand. Witness. Yes, you put the money in my hand in the dark.</p>
               <p>JURY. Q.What hour was it? A. A quarter before eight o'clock - I had never seen the prisoner before, and did not know she was in the house till she came to my bed-side; I suspected it was a house of ill-fame when I got into it, and that made me count my money - I never was in the house before; I am not married.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18310407-280-person1933">
                  JAMES 
                  WALTON
               <interp inst="t18310407-280-person1933" type="surname" value="WALTON"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310407-280-person1933" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310407-280-person1933" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a Police-constable. On the night of the 6th of March I was in Wentworth-street; I was called, and went to the house, where I found the prisoner and the prosecutor on the second floor - the prosecutor was standing in his shirt, and the prisoner in her shift; I took a light with me - there was no light in the room; the prosecutor said she had robbed him of 12s. 6d. - he held out his hands, and said, "Here is what she has given me back," holding a crown-piece in one of his hands, and a half-crown in the other - I took the prisoner to the station-house, but found nothing on her; the prosecutor appeared sensible of what was going on - there was a partition between the room his bed was in and the other; that house makes up from seventy to eighty beds- they are all in narrow slips; the partitions only go up about six or seven feet high - it is more like a rabbit-warren than any thing else; any person might throw any thing over the partition; I have had several charges from that house.</p>
               <p>JURY. Q. What is the sign of the public-house? A. The Two Brewers.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18310407-280-person1934">
                  HENRY 
                  MARQUARD
               <interp inst="t18310407-280-person1934" type="surname" value="MARQUARD"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310407-280-person1934" type="given" value="HENRY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310407-280-person1934" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I was with Walton - I received the crown and half-crown; we could not find any more -I did not observe that there had been a candle in the room, which had been put out.</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence. He had been drinking - he<xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183104070123"></xptr>owned himself he was drinking with another female at the corner.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18310407-280-person1935">
                  JOHN 
                  GARDINER
               <interp inst="t18310407-280-person1935" type="surname" value="GARDINER"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310407-280-person1935" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310407-280-person1935" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . It is false.</p>
